      <hedline>
        <hl1>Loving Cars Less</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>T J Murphy letter on Americans' love of their cars notes worry that dollars spent at gas pump finance governments like Saudi Arabia's that sponsor terrorism (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Ford Heir Says Nation's Affair With the Car Has Lost Its Zip'' (Business Day, Aug. 8):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Ford Heir Says Nation's Affair With the Car Has Lost Its Zip'' (Business Day, Aug. 8):</p>
        <p>William Clay Ford Jr. and the Ford Motor Company may be right to correlate America's lost love for the car with concerns about greenhouse gases and global warming. Another, possibly more pressing worry is the knowledge that dollars spent at the gasoline pump are financing governments like Saudi Arabia's that sponsor terrorism.</p>
        <p>America's love for the automobile could be reignited if our political and corporate leaders embrace a plan to innovate and move our economy away from needing Middle Eastern, or any, foreign oil. Americans are ready to work and sacrifice for the future of our country; this is the way to do it.</p>
        <p>T. J. MURPHY  San Francisco, Aug. 8, 2002</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
